'''Christopher Whyte''' (''Crisdean MhicIlleBhain'') is Scottish poet, novelist, translator and critic.

He was born in [[1952]] in [[Glasgow]] and graduated from [[St. Aloysius' College, Glasgow|St. Aloysius' College]] and then from Cambridge University. For many years he lived in Italy, than moved back to Scotland in 1985 and taught scottisch literature at [[Glasgow University]] from 1990 until 2005. Since then he lives in [[Budapest]] as a full-time writer.

Whyte first published some translations of modern poetry into [[Gaelic]], including poems by [[Pier Paolo Pasolini]] (first publication, [[1980]]), [[Konstantinos Kavafis]], [[Yannis Ritsos]], [[Anna Akhmatova]]. Then he published two collections of original poetry in Gaelic, ''Uirsgeul'' (''Myth'', 1991) and ''An Tr√†th Duilich'' (''The Difficult Time'', 2002). In the meantime he started to write prose in English and published up to this day four novels, ''Euphemia MacFarrigle and the Laughing Virgin'' (1995), ''The Warlock of Strathearn'' (1997), ''The Gay Decameron'' (1998) and ''The Cloud Machinery'' (2000).  Beside this, Whyte compiled some anthologies of present-day Gaelic poetry and appeared with critical articles and essays.


